  "text": "## LLVM Pass Manager Registration and Execution Chain\n\nThe LLVM pass management system uses a sophisticated template-based architecture to support modular and composable optimization passes. Here's the complete registration and execution chain:\n\n### 1. PassManager Template (llvm/include/llvm/IR/PassManager.h, line 162)\nThe core `PassManager<IRUnitT, AnalysisManagerT, ExtraArgTs...>` template provides the infrastructure for managing sequences of passes. Key methods:\n- `addPass(PassT &&Pass)` (line 195): Adds passes to the pipeline using a PassModel wrapper\n- `run(IRUnitT &IR, AnalysisManagerT &AM, ExtraArgTs... ExtraArgs)` (line 190): Executes all passes in sequence over the given IR unit\n- Common instantiations: `ModulePassManager` (line 238) for module-level passes and `FunctionPassManager` (line 247) for function-level passes\n\n### 2. PassConcept and PassModel (llvm/include/llvm/IR/PassManagerInternal.h)\nThe polymorphic dispatch system that enables type-erased pass storage:\n- `PassConcept<IRUnitT, AnalysisManagerT, ExtraArgTs...>` (line 40): Abstract base class defining the polymorphic interface for passes\n- `PassModel<IRUnitT, PassT, AnalysisManagerT, ExtraArgTs...>` (line 72): Template wrapper that implements PassConcept for any pass type\nWhen a pass is added via `addPass()`, it's wrapped in a PassModel and stored as a unique_ptr<PassConcept> in the Passes vector (line 225 of PassManager.h).\n\n### 3. PassRegistry (llvm/include/llvm/PassRegistry.h and llvm/lib/IR/PassRegistry.cpp)\nThe legacy pass registry system (still used for some passes):\n- Singleton instance accessed via `PassRegistry::getPassRegistry()` (line 23-26 of PassRegistry.cpp)\n- `registerPass(const PassInfo &PI)` (line 48): Registers a pass with its type ID and argument string\n- Maintains two maps: PassInfoMap (indexed by type ID) and PassInfoStringMap (indexed by pass name)\n\n### 4. PassRegistry.def (llvm/lib/Passes/PassRegistry.def)\nA macro-based registry file that defines all available passes using patterns like:\n- `MODULE_ANALYSIS(NAME, CREATE_PASS)` (line 21): Module-level analyses\n- `MODULE_PASS(NAME, CREATE_PASS)` (line 54): Module-level transformation passes\n- `FUNCTION_PASS(NAME, CREATE_PASS)`: Function-level passes\n\nThis file is included multiple times in PassBuilder.cpp to generate code for constructing passes.\n\n### 5. PassBuilder (llvm/include/llvm/Passes/PassBuilder.h)\nThe central class for constructing optimization pipelines:\n- Constructor (line 135): Takes TargetMachine, PipelineTuningOptions, PGOOptions, etc.\n- `buildPerModuleDefaultPipeline(OptimizationLevel Level, ThinOrFullLTOPhase Phase)` (line 258): Creates the standard pipeline for O0/O1/O2/O3/Os/Oz optimization levels\n- This is the main entry point for pass pipeline construction\n\n### 6. Pipeline Building Chain (llvm/lib/Passes/PassBuilderPipelines.cpp)\n\n**buildPerModuleDefaultPipeline()** (line 1715-1761):\n- Entry point for all optimization level pipelines\n- Calls `buildModuleSimplificationPipeline(Level, Phase)` (line 1746) to add early simplification passes\n- Calls `buildModuleOptimizationPipeline(Level, Phase)` (line 1749) to add main optimization passes\n- Structure allows O2 and O3 to reuse the same pipeline with different parameter tuning\n\n**buildModuleSimplificationPipeline()** (line 1090-1476):\n- Adds early function passes via EarlyFPM (line 1142-1154):\n  - SimplifyCFGPass\n  - SROAPass\n  - EarlyCSEPass\n  - CallSiteSplittingPass (O3 only, line 1151-1152)\n- Adds module-level optimizations:\n  - OpenMPOptPass (line 1178)\n  - IPSCCPPass (line 1198)\n  - GlobalOptPass (line 1209)\n- Adds inlining infrastructure passes\n\n**buildModuleOptimizationPipeline()** (line 1477-1713):\n- Adds late optimizations:\n  - PartialInlinerPass (line 1486)\n  - EliminateAvailableExternallyPass (line 1498)\n  - ReversePostOrderFunctionAttrsPass (line 1503)\n  - RecomputeGlobalsAAPass (line 1528)\n  - GlobalAnalyses infrastructure (line 1527-1528)\n- Main optimization loop (line 1532-1713) via OptimizePM:\n  - Loop optimizations (LICM, loop unrolling, etc.)\n  - Vectorization passes\n  - Late scalar optimizations\n  - Dead code elimination and cleanup\n\n### 7. Pass Execution Order in O2/O3 Pipelines\n\nFor O2 and O3 optimization levels, the execution order follows this pattern:\n\n1. **Module-level initial passes**: Annotation conversion, attribute forcing\n2. **Simplification pipeline** (via buildModuleSimplificationPipeline):\n   - Early function cleanup (SimplifyCFG, SROA, EarlyCSE)\n   - Global variable optimizations (GlobalOpt)\n   - Interprocedural analysis (IPSCCP, CalledValuePropagation)\n3. **Optimization pipeline** (via buildModuleOptimizationPipeline):\n   - Inlining with iterative simplification (ModuleInlinerWrapperPass)\n   - Function-level optimizations (LICM, GVN, MemCpyOpt, DSE)\n   - Loop optimizations (loop unrolling, distribution)\n   - Vectorization (LoopVectorizePass, SLPVectorizerPass)\n   - Late cleanup passes (LoopSink, DivRemPairs, SimplifyCFG)\n\nKey differences for O3:\n- Line 1151-1152: CallSiteSplittingPass is enabled in O3 only\n- PipelineTuningOptions control loop unrolling, vectorization, and other heuristics\n\n### 8. PassManager.cpp (llvm/lib/IR/PassManager.cpp)\nProvides explicit template instantiations for common types:\n- Template instantiation for PassManager<Module> (line 235)\n- Template instantiation for PassManager<Function> (line 244)\n- Ensures binary compatibility and reduces compilation overhead\n\n### 9. Adding a New Pass to the Pipeline\n\nTo add a new optimization pass to the standard O2/O3 pipeline:\n1. Define the pass class implementing the `run()` method that returns `PreservedAnalyses`\n2. Register it in PassRegistry.def using `MODULE_PASS(\"pass-name\", PassConstructor())`\n3. Add `MPM.addPass(YourPass())` at the appropriate location in buildModuleOptimizationPipeline() or buildModuleSimplificationPipeline()\n4. The PassBuilder will handle construction and PassManager will handle execution via the polymorphic PassConcept/PassModel system\n\nThe design separates pass registration (what passes exist), pipeline construction (which passes run), and execution (how they run), allowing flexible composition of optimization strategies."
}

